Order by: direction, multi-column, and nulls.

Order by sorts the result set, and a few rules are worth carrying. Direction is per column: order by a ascending, then b descending, sorts ascending by a, then breaks ties descending by b. Ascending is the default.

You can sort by an expression or by a select alias, because select runs before order by, so the aliases are visible. But null ordering is dialect-defined. Postgres puts nulls last for ascending and first for descending. MySQL and sequel server put them first either way. Use explicit nulls first or nulls last when it matters; that is standard sequel, supported by Postgres, DuckDB, Oracle, and Snowflake.

One thing to avoid: ordering by ordinal position, like order by one, three. It is terse, but it breaks the moment someone reorders the select list.

The example sorts customers by signup date descending, then by email ascending with nulls last, then by name ascending as a final tie-breaker. The explicit nulls last makes Carol's missing email sort to the bottom no matter which dialect runs it.
